You can use the following code to divide 1000 by 27 in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    double num = 1000;
    double div = 27;
    cout << "The division is: " << (num / div) << endl;
}
```

This code will output:
"The division is: 37.037"

Explanation:
In this case, `num` and `div` are declared as `double`, allowing for floating-point division. The expression `(num / div)` evaluates to approximately 37.037, which includes the decimal part of the result.

If you want to obtain only the integer quotient without any decimal places, you can keep them as integers but note that it will truncate any fractional part:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int num = 1000;
    int div = 27;
    cout << "The integer division is: " << (num / div) << endl; // Outputs: The integer division is: 37
}
```

This approach gives you an integer result of `37`, discarding any remainder from the calculation.

