To extract and display the dates and locations of historical events mentioned in the text of the First Amendment using Java, you can utilize regular expressions. Below is a sample code that demonstrates how to achieve this:

```java
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class HistoricalEventExtractor {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String firstAmendmentText = "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances.";

        // Regular expression patterns for dates (e.g., "July 4, 1776") and locations (e.g., "Philadelphia")
        String datePattern = "\\b\\w+ \\d{1,2}, \\d{4}\\b"; // Matches dates like July 4, 1776
        String locationPattern = "\\b[A-Z][a-z]+(?: [A-Z][a-z]+)*\\b"; // Matches capitalized words as potential locations

        Pattern patternDate = Pattern.compile(datePattern);
        Matcher matcherDate = patternDate.matcher(firstAmendmentText);

        System.out.println("Dates found:");

        while (matcherDate.find()) {
            System.out.println(matcherDate.group());
        }


         Pattern patternLocation = Pattern.compile(locationPattern);
         Matcher matcherLocation = patternLocation.matcher(firstAmendmentText);

         System.out.println("\nLocations found:");

         while (matcherLocation.find()) {
             System.out.println(matcherLocation.group());
         }
    }
}
```

This code defines two regex patterns: one for matching dates formatted as "Month Day, Year" and another for identifying capitalized words that may represent locations. It then searches through a string containing text related to historical events from which it extracts relevant information. The results are printed in a simple format.

