To send a PDF in a web service as JSON in base64 and split it into 4MB requests, you can follow these steps using .NET:

1. **Read the PDF File**: Load the PDF file into memory.

2. **Convert to Base64**: Convert the entire PDF file to a base64 string.

3. **Split Base64 String**: Divide the base64 string into chunks of up to 4MB each.

4. **Send Each Chunk as JSON**: Create a JSON object for each chunk and send it via your web service.

Here’s an example implementation:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Text;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main(string[] args)
    {
        string pdfFilePath = "path/to/your/file.pdf";
        byte[] pdfBytes = File.ReadAllBytes(pdfFilePath);

        // Convert to Base64
        string base64String = Convert.ToBase64String(pdfBytes);

        // Split into chunks of 4MB (approximately)
        int chunkSize = 4096 * 1024; // 4 MB
        int totalChunks = (int)Math.Ceiling((double)base64String.Length / chunkSize);

        using HttpClient client = new HttpClient();

        for (int i = 0; i < totalChunks; i++)
        {
            int startIndex = i * chunkSize;
            int length = Math.Min(chunkSize, base64String.Length - startIndex);
            string chunkData = base64String.Substring(startIndex, length);

            var jsonContent = new 
            {
                ChunkNumber = i + 1,
                TotalChunks= totalChunks,
                Data=chunkData
            };

            var jsonResponseBody= JsonSerializer.Serialize(jsonContent);

            var contentToSend= new StringContent(jsonResponseBody, Encoding.UTF8,"application/json");

           await client.PostAsync("https://yourapi.com/upload", contentToSend); 

           Console.WriteLine($"Sent chunk {i + 1} of {totalChunks}");
       }
   }
}
```

Make sure you replace `"path/to/your/file.pdf"` with your actual file path and `"https://yourapi.com/upload"` with your actual endpoint URL. This code reads the PDF file, converts it to a Base64 encoded string, splits that string into manageable chunks not exceeding approximately four megabytes each, then sends those chunks one by one as JSON

